Introduction

A triangle mesh is a type of polygon mesh constructed over some 2D spaces. It comprises a set of triangles that are connected by their common edges or vertices covering the space under concern. The Triangulation package is a comprehensive collection of tools for generating and visualizing triangle meshes of a 2D domain of arbitrary shape. Triangulation is widely used in various areas, such as computer graphics, Geography, Environmental science, Medical studies, and Statistics.

This package contains two main functions, (i) the triangle mesh generator, TriMesh(), and (ii) the visualization function for triangulations, TriPlot(). It also includes the datasets which are necessary for multiple toy examples, such as the boundary of a horseshoe domain (horseshoe), boundary of Bandiagara island (BMP), and boundaries of irregular shapes (shape and weird).

The function TriMesh() makes use of the exact Delaunay Triangulation to triangulate the domain. There are also some other Delaunay triangulation methods, namely, constrained Delaunay triangulations, conforming Delaunay triangulations, Voronoi diagrams, and high-quality triangular meshes. We will focus only on the exact method in this blog.

How to install

The Triangulation package is currently available on GitHub. To install the package directly from GitHub, first we need another R package, devtools. It can be installed as follows:

install.packages("devtools")

Now, the Triangulation package can be installed using the following code:

library(devtools)
devtools::install_github('FIRST-Data-Lab/Triangulation')

Next, we need to load the Triangulation package to use:

library(Triangulation)

Diifferent datasets and functions available in Triangulation

For detailed information on each of the data (BMP, horseshoe, shape, weird) and function (TriMesh() and TriPlot()) available on Triangulation, please refer to the R documentation.

How to use

This section will discuss the practical implementation of the Triangulation package on a few datasets that are supposed to cover different types of domains that we usually come across in real-life scenarios.

A simple square domain

First, we consider a basic rectangular domain(without any hole) defined on \([0, 2] \times [0, 1]\)

bb = rbind(c(0,0), c(2,0), c(2,1), c(0,1), c(0, 0))
plot(bb, type = "l", col = 2)

The TriMesh() function can then be used to triangulate the domain using the Delaunay triangulation

VT = TriMesh(Pt = bb, n = 10, H = NULL)

  • Pt : A \(N \times 2\) matrix which indicates the outer boundry points of the 2D region.
  • n : An integer parameter controlling the fineness of the triangulation.
  • H : A list of vertices that denotes the inner boundary points(when holes are present).

The output of TriMesh() contain two components:

  • V : \(N\) (number of vertices) \(\times 2\) matrix, with ith row being the Cartesian coordinates for the ith vertex in the triangulation.

  • Tr : \(K\) (Total no. of triangles) \(\times 3\) matrix, with each row representing one triangle. All the elements in a row, are the integers that stand for the indices of vertices in \(V\).

The total number of vertices created is same as the number of rows of V:

# The total number of vertices created
nrow(VT$V)
## [1] 231

The total number of triangles generated is the same as the number of rows of Tr:

# The total number of triangles generated
nrow(VT$Tr)
## [1] 400

The argument n in TriMesh() can be used to fine tune the mesh construction. Greater the value of n, the finer the triangulation becomes. With n = 20 (instead of 10 as in the previous instance), we have:

VT = TriMesh(Pt = bb, n = 20, H = NULL)

# The total number of vertices created
nrow(VT$V)
## [1] 861
# The total number of triangles generated
nrow(VT$Tr)
## [1] 1600

With finer triangulation (i.e., with higher n), the number of vertices and the number of triangles generated also increases.

Even though we get the plot of the triangulated domain from TriMesh(), we can also obtain the same plot using

TriPlot(VT$V, VT$Tr)

Complex irregular domains

1. Horseshoe domain

The horseshoe domain reflects the real life scenario where the domain is almost divided into two parts by a strict concavity with a very narrow gap between the two segments of the domain.

Some boundary points(coordinates) of Horseshoe domain are

head(horseshoe)
##              V1           V2
## 1 -9.000000e-01 1.102146e-16
## 2 -7.534498e-01 4.922533e-01
## 3 -4.283527e-01 7.915264e-01
## 4  5.510729e-17 9.000000e-01
## 5  3.000000e+00 9.000000e-01
## 6  3.240297e+00 8.197771e-01

The boundary of the domain is as follows:

data("horseshoe")
plot(horseshoe, type = "l", col = 2)

Then the triangulation can be done as follows

VT = TriMesh(Pt = horseshoe, n = 8)

2. Irregular domain with holes : BMP data

The BMP data contains a list of coordinates of the boundary vertices of Bandiagara, a small town in Mali. It mimics the situation where the closed bounded domain contains some holes in it.

data("BMP")
plot(BMP$bound, type = "l", col = 2)
lines(BMP$H1, type = "l", col = 2)
lines(BMP$H2, type = "l", col = 2)

Triangulation of the domain:

VT = TriMesh(Pt = BMP$bound, n = 25,
           H = list(as.matrix(BMP$H1), as.matrix(BMP$H2)))

3. US map

Now let us triangulate the US map region using Triangulation. The US boundary can be obtained as follows:

US_bound <- read.csv("boundusa6.csv", header=T)
head(US_bound[ , 2:3])
##           V1       V2
## 1 -122.59593 49.05139
## 2 -114.97487 49.05139
## 3 -106.02840 49.05139
## 4  -98.87123 49.05139
## 5  -94.89502 49.44901
## 6  -90.72001 48.18988
US_bound <- rbind(US_bound, US_bound[1, ])

The boundary points then can be joined to get the polygon representing the US map:

plot(US_bound[ , 2:3], type = "l", col = 2)

Then, using TriMesh(), we get the triangulation of the US map region:

VT = TriMesh(Pt = US_bound[ , 2:3], n = 15, H = NULL)

Few notes to consider

  • The parameter n in the TriMesh() function should be chosen in such a way that
    • the triangles that are generated are more or less uniform in size;
    • the angles of the triangles are not too acute.
  • To apply TriMesh(), we need to have the polygonal vertices that represent the outer boundary of the domain under consideration and the boundary of the holes in it.
